			<exercise label="sov-cq-tf">
				<title>True or False</title>

				<task label="sov-cq-tf-01">
					<title>üëçüëé</title>
					<statement correct="no">
						<p>
							Every first-order ordinary differential equation can be solved using the method of separation of variables.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							False. Only first-order ordinary differential equation that are <term>separable</term> can be solved using the method of separation of variables.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-tf-02">
					<title>üëçüëé</title>
					<statement correct="no">
						<p>
							If a differential equation is separable, its solution will always be an explicit function of <m> x </m>.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							False. The solution to a separable differential equation is sometimes implicit function of the independent variable.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-tf-03">
					<title>üëçüëé</title>
					<statement correct="no">
						<p>
							The method of separation of variables can be applied to some second order differential equations, but not all of them.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							False. The method of separation of variables is only applicable to <term>first-order</term> separable differential equations.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-tf-04">
					<title>üëçüëé</title>
					<statement correct="yes">
						<p>
							Any differential equation that can be written in the form
							<me>
								h(y) \frac{dy}{dx} = g(x)
							</me>,
							is separable.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							True. Any differential equation that can be written in the form
							<me>
								h(y) \frac{dy}{dx} = g(x)
							</me>
							can also be rewritten in the separable form
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = g(x)\cdot \frac{1}{h(y)}
							</me>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-tf-05">
					<title>üëçüëé</title>
					<statement correct="yes">
						<p>
							The differential equation, below, is <xref ref="separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{\cos x}{y}
							</me>
						</p>
					</statement>
						<p>
							The correct answer is:
						</p>
						<p>
							A. It is always separable.
						</p>
						<p>
							This differential equation is the same as
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = g(x) \cdot (1)
							</me>,
							which shows that the equation is separable since the function of <m>y</m> can be constant.
						</p>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The equation is separable because it is first-order and can be written in the separable form
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = \cos x \left(\frac{1}{y}\right)
							</me>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</task>
				
				<task label="sov-cq-tf-06">
					<title>üëçüëé</title>
					<statement correct="yes">
						<p>
							The differential equation, below, is <xref ref="separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2
							</me>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The equation is separable because it is first-order and can be written in the separable form
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2 = (1)(y^2) = \underset{f(x)}{\left(\boxed{1}\right)}\underset{g(y)}{\left(\boxed{y^2}\right)}
							</me>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</task>
					
				<task label="sov-cq-tf-07">
					<title>üëçüëé</title>
					<statement correct="yes">
						<p>
							The differential equation, below, is <xref ref="separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = x - 1
							</me>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The equation is separable because it is first-order and can be written in the separable form
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = x - 1 = (x - 1)(1) = \underset{f(x)}{\left(\boxed{x - 1}\right)}\underset{g(y)}{\left(\boxed{1}\right)}.
							</me>
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-tf-08">
					<title>üëçüëé</title>
					<statement correct="yes">
						<p>
							The differential equation, below, is <xref ref="separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = 15
							</me>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The equation is separable because it is first-order and can be written in the separable form
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = 15 = (15)(1) = \underset{f(x)}{\left(\boxed{15}\right)}\underset{g(y)}{\left(\boxed{1}\right)}.
							</me>
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-tf-09">
					<title>üëçüëé</title>
					<statement correct="no">
						<p>
							The differential equation,
							<me>
								x + \frac{dy}{dx} = y
							</me>,
							can be solved using the separation of variables method.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The differential equation is first order, but it is equivalent to
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx}=y-x
							</me>,
							which can not be written in the form <m>\ds\frac{dy}{dx}=f(x)g(y)</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
					<hint>
						<p>
							Check to see that the differential equation is first order and separable.
						</p>
					</hint>
				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-tf-10">
					<title>üëçüëé</title>
					<statement correct="no">
						<p>
							The differential equation,
							<me>
								\frac{dz^2}{d^2t} = \cos^2(z)
							</me>,
							can be solved using the separation of variables method.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							The differential equation is not first order, so it is not separable and cannot be solved using the separation of variables method.
						</p>
					</feedback>
					<hint>
						<p>
							Check to see that the differential equation is first order and separable.
						</p>
					</hint>
				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-tf-11">
					<title><e component="emoji">üìñ‚ùì</e> SOV and Nonlinear Equations</title>

					<statement correct="no">
						<p>
							The separation of variables method cannot be applied to non-linear differential equations.
						</p>
					</statement>

					<feedback>
						<p>
							Being able to solve non-linear differential equations is one of the strengths of the separation of variables method.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</task>
			</exercise>

			<exercise label="sov-cq-mc">
				<title>Multiple Choice</title>

				<task label="sov-cq-mc-01">
					<title>Initial Step</title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							What is the first step to verify the differential equation below is separable?
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} + \frac{x}{y^2} = 0
							</me>
						</p>
					</statement>

					<choices randomize="yes">
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<p>
									Integrating both sides with respect to <m>x</m>.
								</p>
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Incorrect. Integration should come after the equation is verified to be separable.
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement>
								<p>
									Check to make sure the equation is first order.
								</p>
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Correct! The first step to verify the equation is separable is to make sure it is first order.
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<p>
									Combine the fractions on the left-side of the equation.
								</p>
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Incorrect. First of all, <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m> is not a fraction. Even if it was this would not be the first step to verify separability.
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<p>
									Isolate <m>\ds\frac{dy}{dx}</m> on one side of the equation.
								</p>
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Incorrect. Isolating <m>\ds\frac{dy}{dx}</m> is required to verify the equation is separable, but there is one other detail to check first.
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
					</choices>

				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-mc-02">
					<title>Select the Separable Equations</title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							Click on each of the separable differential equations below.
						</p>
					</statement>

					<areas>
						<tabular>
							<row><cell><m/></cell></row>
							<row>
								<cell><area correct="yes">
									<m>\quad\ds x^2\frac{dy}{dx} - y = x^2y</m>
								</area></cell><cell/>
								<cell><area correct="no">
									<m>\quad\dfrac{dy}{dx} + xy = y^2</m>
								</area></cell>
							</row>
							<row><cell><m/></cell></row>
							<row>
								<cell><area correct="yes">
									<m>\quad\ds \sqrt{x^2+1}\frac{dy}{dx} = y</m>
								</area></cell>
								<cell/>
								<cell><area correct="no">
									<m>\quad\ds xy\frac{dy}{dx} = x + y</m>
								</area></cell>
							</row>
							<row><cell><m/></cell></row>
							<row>
								<cell><area correct="yes">
									<m>\quad\ds x\frac{dy}{dx} - e^x = 3</m>
								</area></cell>
								<cell/>
								<cell><area correct="no">
									<m>\quad\dfrac{dy}{dx} - x = \dfrac{y^2}{x}</m>
								</area></cell>
							</row>
							<row><cell><m/></cell></row>
						</tabular>
					</areas>

					<feedback>
						<p>
							A differential equation is separable if you can rearrange it to express it as a product of functions involving only <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> separately. Look for equations that can be manipulated into this form, even if they do not initially appear separable.
						</p>
					</feedback>

				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-mc-03">
					<title>When is it Separable?</title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							What can you say about any differential equation that can be written in the form
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = g(x)
							</me>?
						</p>
					</statement>

					<choices randomize="yes">
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement>
								<p>
									It is always separable.
								</p>
							</statement>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<p>
									It is never separable.
								</p>
							</statement>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<p>
									It might be separable, depending on <m>g(x)</m>.
								</p>
							</statement>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<p>
									It is not a valid equation because it does have a <m>y</m> term.
								</p>
							</statement>
						</choice>
					</choices>

				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-mc-04">
					<title>Explicit or Implicit?</title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							Which of the following equations represent an <term>implicit</term> solution to a differential equation?
						</p>
						<p>
							<em>Assume <m>y</m> is the dependent variable and <m>t</m> is the independent variable.</em>
						</p>
					</statement>

					<choices randomize="yes">
						<choice>
							<statement><m>y = \tan(t) + c</m></statement>
							<feedback><p>No, this is an explicit solution since <m>y</m> is written as a function of <m>t</m>.</p></feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement><m>y^2 + \ln y = t + c</m></statement>
							<feedback><p>Correct. You can't isolate <m>y</m> without solving a nonlinear equation, so this is an implicit solution.</p></feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement><m>y^2 + 2e^{y} = t^2 - 2</m></statement>
							<feedback><p>Yes, this matches the example you just saw and defines <m>y</m> only implicitly.</p></feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement><m>y = \tan(t + c)</m></statement>
							<feedback><p>No, this is an explicit expression for <m>y</m> as a function of <m>t</m>.</p></feedback>
						</choice>
					</choices>

				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-mc-05">
					<title>When Does SOV Apply?</title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							Which two properties must a differential equation satisfy in order to solve it using the separation of variables method?
						</p>
					</statement>

					<choices randomize="yes">
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<p>
									The equation must be linear and separable.
								</p>
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Incorrect. Separable is required, but the equation does not need to be linear.
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<p>
									The equation must be first-order and linear.
								</p>
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Incorrect. First-order is required, but the equation does not need to be linear for the separation of variables method to be applied.
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<p>
									The equation must be second-order and separable.
								</p>
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Incorrect. Separable is required, but the equation cannot be second-order for the separation of variables method to be applied.
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement>
								<p>
									The equation must be first-order and separable.
								</p>
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Correct! The separation of variables method applies only to first-order differential equations thatare separable.
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
					</choices>

				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-mc-06">
					<title>Combining Constants</title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							Which of the following are valid ways to combine constants when finalizing your solution? Select ALL that apply.
						</p>
					</statement>

					<choices randomize="yes">
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										|y|	\amp = e^{2x + c_1}\\ 
										y	\amp = c_2 e^{2x} 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_2=\pm e^{c_1}</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Correct, since
									<md>
										<mrow>	|y|	\amp =,	e^{2x + c_1}										</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\pm e^{2x + c_1}									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\pm e^{2x} \cdot e^{c_1}							</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	c_2 e^{2x}	\quad \text{where } c_2 = \pm e^{c_1}	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										\frac{y^2}{2} \amp = \sin(x) + c_1\\ 
										y^2 \amp = 2\sin(x) + c_2 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_2 = 2c_1</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Correct, since
									<md>
										<mrow>	\frac{y^2}{2}	\amp =,	\sin(x) + c_1									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y^2				\amp =,	\sin(x) + 2c_1									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y^2				\amp =,	2\sin(x) + c_2	\quad \text{where } c_2 = 2c_1	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										y^2	\amp = 2\sin(x) + c_2\\ 
										y	\amp = \pm\sqrt{2\sin(x)} + c_3 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_3=\pm \sqrt{c_2}</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Incorrect, you should not combine constants here since <m>\quad\sqrt{A + B} \neq \sqrt{A} + \sqrt{B}</m>.
								</p>

								<p>
									Your solution should be written as
									<md>
										<mrow>	y^2	\amp =,	2\sin(x) + c_2											</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\pm\sqrt{2\sin(x) + c_2}\quad \leftarrow\text{ done}	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										e^y	\amp =	3y + c_1\\ 
										y	\amp =	\ln(3y) + c_2 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_2= \ln(c_1)</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								
								<p>
									Incorrect, you should not combine constants here since <m>\ln(A + B) \neq \ln(A) + \ln(B)</m>.
								</p>

								<p>
									Your solution should be
									<md>
										<mrow>	e^y	\amp =,	3y + c_1									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\ln(3y + c_1)\quad \leftarrow\text{ done}	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										xy	\amp =	e^x + c_1\\ 
										y	\amp =	\frac{e^x}{x} + c_2 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_2=\frac{c_1}{x}</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Incorrect, you should not combine constants here since <m>\frac{c_1}{x}</m> is not constant. Instead your solution should be left as
									<md>
										<mrow>	xy	\amp =,	e^x + c_1													</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\frac{e^x + c_1}{x}											</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\frac{e^x}{x} + \frac{c_1}{x}\quad \leftarrow\text{ done}	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										\sqrt{y}	\amp =	c_1e^{3x}\\ 
										y			\amp =	c_2\, e^{6x} 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_2= c_1^2</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Correct, since
									<md>
										<mrow>	\sqrt{y}	\amp =,	c_1e^{3x}									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y			\amp =,	(c_1e^{3x})^2								</mrow>
										<mrow>	y			\amp =,	c_1^2(e^{3x})^2								</mrow>
										<mrow>	y			\amp =,	c_2\, e^{6x}\quad \text{where } c_2 = c_1^2	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
					</choices>

				</task>
			</exercise>

			<exercise label="sov-cq-sa">
				<title>Short-Answer Questions</title>

				<task label="sov-cq-sa-01">
					<title>Not Separable</title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							Give an example of a differential equation that is not separable.
						</p>
					</statement>

					<response />

					<feedback>
						<p>
							An example of a differential equation that is not separable is <m> \frac{dy}{dx} = y + x^2 </m>. This equation is not separable because the terms involving <m>y</m> and <m>x</m> are not easily separable onto different sides of the equation. In this case, the method of separation of variables cannot be applied because the terms involving <m>y</m> and <m>x</m> are not easily separable.
						</p>
					</feedback>

				</task>
			
				<task label="sov-cq-sa-02">
					<title>Where Does <q>Separation of Variables</q> Come From?</title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							Explain why you think <q>separation of variables</q> is an appropriate name for the method in this chapter.
						</p>
					</statement>

					<response />

					<feedback>
						<p>
							The method of separation of variables is named as such because it involves isolating all terms involving <m>y</m> to one side and all terms involving <m>x</m> to the other. This effectively separates the variables <m>y</m> and <m>x</m> onto different sides of the equation, allowing for the integration of each side independently. The name "separation of variables" reflects the process of isolating the variables onto different sides of the equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
					
				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-sa-03">
					<title>What Could go Wrong?</title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							Ignoring the fact that the following equation is not separable, suppose we applied the separation of variables process to
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2 + x
							</me>.
							What breaks down leading up to the <xref ref="sov-step-2" text="custom">integrate step</xref>?
						</p>
					</statement>

					<response />

					<feedback>
						<p>
							The next step in the process says to divide both sides by the function of <m>y</m>. In our case, this is <m>y^2</m>, so we would get
							<me>
								\frac{1}{y^2} \frac{dy}{dx} = 1 + \frac{x}{y^2}
							</me>.
							Now, multiplying both sides by <m>dx</m> and integrating would yield
							<me>
								\int \frac{1}{y^2} dy = \int \left( 1 + \frac{x}{y^2} \right) dx
							</me>.
							The integral on the left side is fine, but the integral on the right side is where the process breaks down since the integral wants to integrate with respect to <m>x</m>. Therefore, you are stuck unless you knew <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m>. However, if this were the case, you would have already solved the problem!
						</p>
					</feedback>

				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-sa-04">
					<title>Implicit vs. Explicit</title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							Some differential equations solved using separation of variables yield explicit solutions, while others yield implicit solutions. Give your interpretation of the difference between an implicit and explicit solution. Provide an example of an implicitly and explicitly defined function.
						</p>
					</statement>

					<response />

					<feedback>
						<p>
							An implicit solution is one where the relationship between <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> is not explicitly defined. For example, the solution <m> x^2 + y^2 = 1 </m> is an implicit solution. An explicit solution, on the other hand, is one where <m>y</m> is defined explicitly as a function of <m>x</m>. For example, the solution <m> y = \sqrt{1 - x^2} </m> is an explicit solution.
						</p>
					</feedback>

				</task>

				<task label="sov-cq-sa-05">
					<title>Thinking in Cases</title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							All first order linear differential equations with dependent variable, <m>y</m>, can be written in the form
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} + P(x) y = Q(x)
							</me>
							where <m>P(x)</m> and <m>Q(x)</m> are known functions of <m>x</m>. What must be true about <m>P(x)</m> and <m>Q(x)</m> for a first-order linear differential equation to be separable?
						</p>
						<hint>
							<p>
								Make some general assumptions about <m>P(x)</m> and <m>Q(x)</m> and think about how you could break this question into different cases about what <m>P(x)</m> and <m>Q(x)</m> could be to guarantee separability.
							</p>
						</hint>
					</statement>

					<response />

					<feedback>
						<p>
							Attempting to isolate the derivative on the left, we get:
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = Q(x) -  P(x) y
							</me>
							Since, <m>Q(x)</m> and <m>P(x)</m> can only contain the variable <m>x</m> or constants, then this form is only separable in the following cases:
							<ol>
								<li>
									Both <m>Q(x) = Q_0</m> and <m>P(x)=P_0</m> are constant. Then
									<me>
										\frac{dy}{dx} = Q_0 - P_0 y = (1) \cdot (Q_0 -  P_0 y)
									</me>
								</li>
								<li>
									<m>Q(x) = 0</m> and <m>P(x)</m> is anything. Then
									<me>
										\frac{dy}{dx} = 0 - P(x) y = (-P(x)) \cdot (y)
									</me>
								</li>
								<li>
									<m>Q(x) = 0</m> is anything and <m>P(x) = 0</m>. Then
									<me>
										\frac{dy}{dx} = Q(x) - (0) y = (Q(x)) \cdot (1)
									</me>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</p>
					</feedback>

					<solution>
						<p>
							Attempting to isolate the derivative on the left, we get:
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = Q(x) -  P(x) y
							</me>
							Since, <m>Q(x)</m> and <m>P(x)</m> can only contain the variable <m>x</m> or constants, then this form is only separable in the following cases:
							<ol>
								<li>
									Both <m>Q(x) = Q_0</m> and <m>P(x)=P_0</m> are constant. Then
									<me>
										\frac{dy}{dx} = Q_0 - P_0 y = (1) \cdot (Q_0 -  P_0 y)
									</me>
								</li>
								<li>
									<m>Q(x) = 0</m> and <m>P(x)</m> is anything. Then
									<me>
										\frac{dy}{dx} = 0 - P(x) y = (-P(x)) \cdot (y)
									</me>
								</li>
								<li>
									<m>Q(x) = 0</m> is anything and <m>P(x) = 0</m>. Then
									<me>
										\frac{dy}{dx} = Q(x) - (0) y = (Q(x)) \cdot (1)
									</me>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</p>
					</solution>
					
				</task>

			</exercise>

		</exercises>

