	<subsection label="sov-practice-drills">
		<title><e component="emoji">üèãÔ∏è‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è</e> Practice Drills</title>

		<exercises label="sov-drills">

			<exercise label="sov-drills-1">
				<title>Verify the solution</title>

				<statement>
					<p>
						Verify that <m>z = \tan(t+C)</m> is a solution to the initial value problem
						<me>z' - 1 = z^2, \quad z(4) = 9</me>
						then find the paticular solution.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> z' - 1 \amp = z^2</mrow>
							<mrow> \frac{d}{dt}\Big( \tan(t+C) \Big) - 1 \amp = \Big( \tan(t+C) \Big)^2</mrow>
							<mrow> \sec^2(t+C)\cdot \frac{d}{dt}(t+C) - 1 \amp = \tan^2(t+C)</mrow>
							<mrow> \sec^2(t+C)\cdot (1+0) - 1 \amp = \sec^2 t - 1</mrow>
							<mrow> \sec^2(t+C) - 1 \amp = \sec^2 t - 1 \quad ‚úÖÔ∏è</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
			
					<p>
						Now, let's find <m>C</m> with the initial condition <m>z(4) = 9</m>:
						<me>9 = z(4) = \tan(4+C)\quad\Rightarrow\quad C = tan^{-1}(9) - 4 \approx 79.66</me>
					</p>

					<p>
						So the (approximate) particular solution is:
						<me>
							z = \tan(t + 79.66) 
						</me>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</exercise>

			<exercise label="sov-drills-2">
				<title>Show the differential equations is separable</title>

				<statement>
					<p><me>t - ss' = - s</me></p>
				</statement>
				
				<solution>
					<p>
						To see that this equation is separable, we need to check that it can be rearranged in <xref ref="separable" text="custom">separable form</xref>. Isolating <m> s' </m> we get
						<me> s' = \frac{s + t}{s} </me>
						and it should be clear that there is no way to separate <m>t</m> and <m>s</m> by <em>multiplication</em> in the numerator, so this equation <em>is not separable</em>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</exercise>

			<exercisegroup cols="2" label="sov-drills-3">
				<title>Separable Form</title>

				<introduction>
					<p>
						Determine whether the given differential equation is separable or not. As demonstrated in the examples, if the equation is separable, use parentheses to explicitly show the separable form.
					</p>
				</introduction>

				<exercise label="sov-drills-3-1">
					<statement><m>\dfrac{dz}{dt} = \sin(z+t)</m></statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							<alert>not</alert> separable; there's no way to separate th <m> \ds z </m> an <m> \ds t </m> inside the sine term.
						</p>
					</solution>
					<answer>
						<p>
							<alert>not</alert> separable
						</p>
					</answer>
				</exercise>

				<exercise label="sov-drills-3-2">
					<statement><m>\ds s' = t\ln(s^{2t}) + 8t^2</m></statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							This doesn't look separable; but if we use a property of logarithms we can re-write as follows.
							<md>
								<mrow>  s'	 \amp =  t\ln(s^{2t}) + 8t^2 </mrow>
								<mrow>  \frac{ds}{dt}	 \amp =  t \cdot 2t\ln(s) + 8t^2 </mrow>
								<mrow>   \amp =  2t^2 \ln(s) + 8t^2 </mrow>
								<mrow>   \amp =  \big(t^2\big)\big(2\ln(s) + 8\big) </mrow>
							</md>
							Hence, this DE is <alert>separable</alert>.
						</p>
					</solution>
					<answer>
						<p>
							<alert>separable</alert>
						</p>
					</answer>
				</exercise>

				<exercise label="sov-drills-3-3">
					<statement><m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 2y^3 + y + 4</m></statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							We can rearrange as follows.
							<md>
								<mrow>  \frac{dy}{dx}	 \amp =  \big(1\big)\big(2y^3 + y + 4\big) </mrow>
							</md>
							Hence, this DE is <alert>separable</alert>.
						</p>
					</solution>
					<answer>
						<p>
							<alert>separable</alert>
						</p>
					</answer>
				</exercise>

				<exercise label="sov-drills-3-4">
					<statement><m>\ds y' - xy = 0</m></statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							We can rearrange as follows.
							<md>
								<mrow>  y' - xy	 \amp =  0 </mrow>
								<mrow>  y'	 \amp =  \big(x\big)\big(y\big) </mrow>
							</md>
							Hence, this DE is <alert>separable</alert>.
						</p>
					</solution>
					<answer>
						<p>
							<alert>separable</alert>
						</p>
					</answer>
				</exercise>

				<exercise label="sov-drills-3-5">
					<statement><m>\ds y' = x+y</m></statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							<alert>not</alert> separable; there's no way to separate <m> \ds x </m> and <m> \ds y </m> via multiplication/division
						</p>
					</solution>
					<answer>
						<p>
							<alert>not</alert> separable
						</p>
					</answer>
				</exercise>

				<exercise label="sov-drills-3-6">
					<statement><m>\ds y'' + y' + y = 0</m></statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							<alert>not</alert> separable; this DE is second order, and DEs must be first order to be separable
						</p>
					</solution>
					<answer>
						<p>
							<alert>not</alert> separable
						</p>
					</answer>
				</exercise>

			</exercisegroup>

		</exercises>

